The origin and development of '''[[water]] on [[terrestrial planet]]s''', [[Venus]], [[Earth]], [[Mars]], and the closely related Earth's [[Moon]], varies with each planetary body, with the exact origins remaining unclear. Additionally, the terrestrial dwarf planet, [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] is known to have water ice on its surface.
== Water inventories== === Mars===
{{Main|Water on Mars}}
A significant amount of surface [[hydrogen]] has been observed globally by the [[Mars]] Odyssey GRS.<ref name = Boynton2007>{{cite journal|last1=Boynton|first1=W. V.|last2=Taylor|first2=G. J.|last3=Evans|first3=L. G.|last4=Reedy|first4=R. C.|last5=Starr|first5=R.|last6=Janes|first6=D. M.|last7=Kerry|first7=K. E.|last8=Drake|first8=D. M.|last9=Kim|first9=K. J.|last10=Williams|first10=R. M. S.|last11=Crombie|first11=M. K.|last12=Dohm|first12=J. M.|last13=Baker|first13=V.|last14=Metzger|first14=A. E.|last15=Karunatillake|first15=S.|last16=Keller|first16=J. M.|last17=Newsom|first17=H. E.|last18=Arnold|first18=J. R.|last19=Brückner|first19=J.|last20=Englert|first20=P. A. J.|last21=Gasnault|first21=O.|last22=Sprague|first22=A. L.|last23=Mitrofanov|first23=I.|last24=Squyres|first24=S. W.|last25=Trombka|first25=J. I.|last26=d'Uston|first26=L.|last27=Wänke|first27=H.|last28=Hamara|first28=D. K.|title=Concentration of H, Si, Cl, K, Fe, and Th in the low- and mid-latitude regions of Mars|journal=Journal of Geophysical Research|date=2007|volume=112|issue=E12|doi=10.1029/2007JE002887|bibcode=2007JGRE..11212S99B}}</ref> Stoichiometrically estimated [[water mass]] fractions indicate that—when free of [[carbon dioxide]]—the near surface at the poles consists almost entirely of water covered by a thin veneer of fine material.<ref name = Boynton2007/> This is reinforced by [[MARSIS]] observations, with an estimated {{convert|1.6e6|km³|abbr=on}} of water at the southern polar region with Water Equivalent to a Global layer (WEG) {{convert|11|m}} deep.<ref name = Plaut2007>{{cite journal|last1=Plaut|first1=J. J.|last2=Picardi|first2=G.|last3=Safaeinili|first3=A.|last4=Ivanov|first4=A. B.|last5=Milkovich|first5=S. M.|last6=Cicchetti|first6=A.|last7=Kofman|first7=W.|last8=Mouginot|first8=J.|last9=Farrell|first9=W. M.|last10=Phillips|first10=R. J.|last11=Clifford|first11=S. M.|last12=Frigeri|first12=A.|last13=Orosei|first13=R.|last14=Federico|first14=C.|last15=Williams|first15=I. P.|last16=Gurnett|first16=D. A.|last17=Nielsen|first17=E.|last18=Hagfors|first18=T.|last19=Heggy|first19=E.|last20=Stofan|first20=E. R.|last21=Plettemeier|first21=D.|last22=Watters|first22=T. R.|last23=Leuschen|first23=C. J.|last24=Edenhofer|first24=P.|title=Subsurface Radar Sounding of the South Polar Layered Deposits of Mars|journal=Science|date=2007|volume=316|issue=5821|pages=92–95|doi=10.1126/science.1139672|bibcode=2007Sci...316...92P}}</ref> Additional observations at both poles suggest the total WEG to be {{convert|30|m|abbr=on}}, while the Mars Odyssey NS observations places the lower bound at ~{{convert|14|cm|abbr=on}} depth.<ref name = Feldman2004>{{cite journal|last1=Feldman|first1=W. C.|title=Global distribution of near-surface hydrogen on Mars|journal=Journal of Geophysical Research|date=2004|volume=109|issue=E9|doi=10.1029/2003JE002160|bibcode=2004JGRE..109.9006F}}</ref> Geomorphic evidence favors significantly larger quantities of [[surface water]] over geologic history, with WEG as deep as {{convert|500|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name = Feldman2004/> The current atmospheric reservoir of water, though important as a conduit, is insignificant in volume with the WEG no more than {{convert|10|µm|abbr=on}}.<ref name = Feldman2004/> Since the typical [[surface pressure]] of the current atmosphere (~{{convert|6|hPa|abbr=on}}<ref name = Jakosky2001>{{cite journal|last1=Jakosky|first1=B. M.|last2=Phillips|first2=R. J.|journal=Nature|date=2001|volume=412|issue=6843|pages=237–244|doi=10.1038/35084184|title=Mars' volatile and climate history}}</ref>) is less than the triple point of H<sub>2</sub>O, liquid water is unstable on the surface unless present in [[sufficiently large]] volumes. Furthermore, the average global temperature is ~{{convert|220|K|C F}}, even below the eutectic [[freezing point]] of most brines.<ref name = Jakosky2001/> For comparison, the highest diurnal surface temperatures at the two MER sites have been ~{{convert|290|K|C F}}.<ref name = Spanovich2006>{{cite journal|last1=Spanovich|first1=N.|last2=Smith|first2=M. D.|last3=Smith|first3=P. H.|last4=Wolff|first4=M. J.|last5=Christensen|first5=P. R.|last6=Squyres|first6=S. W.|title=Surface and near-surface atmospheric temperatures for the Mars Exploration Rover landing sites|journal=Icarus|date=2006|volume=180|issue=2|pages=314–320|doi=10.1016/j.icarus.2005.09.014|bibcode=2006Icar..180..314S}}</ref>
===Mercury, Moon, and Earth===
{{Main|Lunar water}}
Recent observation made by a number of spacecraft confirmed significant amounts of [[Lunar water]]. Mercury does not appear to contain observable quantities of H<sub>2</sub>O, presumably due to loss from giant impacts.<ref name = Drake2005/> In contrast, Earth's hydrosphere contains ~{{convert|1.46e21|kg|abbr=on}} of H<sub>2</sub>O and [[sedimentary rock]]s contain ~{{convert|0.21e21|kg|abbr=on}}, for a total crustal inventory of ~{{convert|1.67e21|kg|abbr=on}} of H<sub>2</sub>O.<ref name = Kulikov2006/> The mantle inventory is poorly constrained in the range of {{convert|0.5e21-4e21|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref name = Morbidelli2000>{{cite journal|last1=Morbidelli|first1=A.|last2=Chambers|first2=J.|last3=Lunine|first3=J. I.|last4=Petit|first4=J. M.|last5=Robert|first5=F.|last6=Valsecchi|first6=G. B.|last7=Cyr|first7=K. E.|title=Source regions and timescales for the delivery of water to the Earth|journal=Meteoritics & Planetary Science|date=2000|volume=35|issue=6|pages=1309–1320|doi=10.1111/j.1945-5100.2000.tb01518.x|bibcode=2000M&PS...35.1309M}}</ref> Therefore, the bulk inventory of H<sub>2</sub>O on Earth can be conservatively estimated as 0.04% of Earth's mass (~{{convert|2.3e21|kg|abbr=on}}).
===Venus===
{{Main|Atmosphere of Venus}}
The current Venusian atmosphere has only ~200&nbsp;mg/kg H<sub>2</sub>O(g) in its atmosphere and the pressure and temperature regime makes water unstable on its surface. Nevertheless, assuming that early Venus's H<sub>2</sub>O had a D/H ratio similar to Earth's Vienna Standard Mean Ocean Water ([[VSMOW]]) of 1.6×10<sup>−4</sup>,<ref name = NIST>[[National Institute of Standards and Technology]] (2005), [https://srmors.nist.gov/certificates/8535.pdf?CFID=12001608&CFTOKEN=5c24bc7fc8132ce6-2B2520A5-A7C5-6123-0D31F83B0741932B&jsessionid=b430d26f379de78357e1 Report of Investigation]</ref> the current D/H isotopic ratio in the Venusian atmosphere of 1.9×10<sup>−2</sup>, at nearly ×120 of Earth's, may indicate that Venus had a much larger H<sub>2</sub>O inventory.<ref name = Kulikov2006>{{cite journal|last1=Kulikov|first1=Yu. N.|last2=Lammer|first2=H.|last3=Lichtenegger|first3=H. I. M.|last4=Terada|first4=N.|last5=Ribas|first5=I.|last6=Kolb|first6=C.|last7=Langmayr|first7=D.|last8=Lundin|first8=R.|last9=Guinan|first9=E. F.|last10=Barabash|first10=S.|last11=Biernat|first11=H. K.|title=Atmospheric and water loss from early Venus|journal=Planetary and Space Science|date=2006|volume=54|issue=13–14|pages=1425–1444|doi=10.1016/j.pss.2006.04.021|bibcode=2006P&SS...54.1425K}}</ref> While the large disparity between terrestrial and Venusian D/H ratios makes any estimation of Venus's geologically ancient water budget difficult,<ref name = Drake2005>{{cite journal|last1=Drake|first1=M. J.|title=Origin of water in the terrestrial planets|journal=Meteoritics & Planetary Science|date=2005|volume=40|issue=4|pages=519–527|doi=10.1111/j.1945-5100.2005.tb00960.x|bibcode=2005M&PS...40..519D}}</ref> its mass may have been at least 0.3% of Earth's hydrosphere.<ref name = Kulikov2006/> Estimates based on Venus's levels of [[deuterium]] suggest that the planet has lost anywhere from {{convert|4|m}} of surface water up to "an Earth's ocean's worth".<ref name = JamesOwen>Owen, (2007), [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2007/11/071128-venus-earth_2.html news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2007/11/071128-venus-earth_2.html]</ref>
==Accretion of water by Earth and Mars==
{{Main|Origin of water on Earth}}
The D/H isotopic ratio is a primary constraint on the source of H<sub>2</sub>O of terrestrial planets. Comparison of the planetary D/H ratios with those of carbonaceous chondrites and comets enables a tentative determination of the source of H<sub>2</sub>O. The best constraints for accreted H<sub>2</sub>O are determined from non-atmospheric H<sub>2</sub>O, as the D/H ratio of the atmospheric component may be subject to rapid alteration by the preferential loss of H <ref name=Jakosky2001/> unless it is in isotopic equilibrium with surface H<sub>2</sub>O. Earth's VSMOW D/H ratio of 1.6×10<sup>−4</sup><ref name=NIST/> and modeling of impacts suggest that the cometary contribution to crustal water was less than 10%. However, much of the water could be derived from Mercury-sized planetary embryos that formed in the [[asteroid belt]] beyond 2.5&nbsp;AU.<ref name = Lunine2003>{{cite journal|last1=Lunine|first1=J. I.|last2=Chambers|first2=J.|last3=Morbidelli|first3=A.|last4=Leshin|first4=L. A.|title=The origin of water on Mars|journal=Icarus|date=2003|volume=165|issue=1|pages=1–8|doi=10.1016/S0019-1035(03)00172-6|bibcode=2003Icar..165....1L}}</ref> Mars's original D/H ratio, as estimated by deconvolving the atmospheric and magmatic D/H components in [[Mars meteorite|Martian meteorites]] (e.g., QUE 94201), is ×(1.9+/-0.25) the VSMOW value.<ref name=Lunine2003/> The higher D/H and impact modeling (significantly different from Earth due to Mars's smaller mass) favor a model where Mars accreted a total of 6% to 27% the mass of the current Earth hydrosphere, corresponding respectively to an original D/H between ×1.6 and ×1.2 the SMOW value.<ref name = Lunine2003/> The former enhancement is consistent with roughly equal asteroidal and cometary contributions, while the latter would indicate mostly asteroidal contributions.<ref name=Lunine2003/> The corresponding WEG would be {{convert|0.6-2.7|km|abbr=on}}, consistent with a 50% outgassing efficiency to yield ~{{convert|500|m|abbr=on}} WEG of surface water.<ref name = Lunine2003/> Comparing the current atmospheric D/H ratio of ×5.5 SMOW ratio with the primordial ×1.6 SMOW ratio suggests that ~{{convert|50|m|abbr=on}} of has been lost to space via [[solar wind]] stripping.<ref name=Lunine2003/>
The cometary and asteroidal delivery of water to accreting Earth and Mars has significant caveats, even though it is favored by D/H isotopic ratios.<ref name=Drake2005/> Key issues include:<ref name=Drake2005/>
# The higher D/H ratios in Martian meteorites could be a consequence of biased sampling since Mars may have never had an effective [[crustal recycling]] process # Earth's Primitive Upper Mantle estimate of the <sup>187</sup>Os/<sup>188</sup>Os isotopic ratio exceeds 0.129, significantly greater than that of carbonaceous chondrites, but similar to anhydrous ordinary chondrites. This makes it unlikely that planetary embryos compositionally similar to carbonaceous chondrites supplied water to Earth # Earth's atmospheric content of Ne is significantly higher than would be expected had all the rare gases and H<sub>2</sub>O been accreted from planetary embryos with carbonaceous chondritic compositions.<ref name = Morbidelli2000/>
An alternative to the cometary and asteroidal delivery of H<sub>2</sub>O would be the accretion via physisorption during the formation of the terrestrial planets in the [[solar nebula]]. This would be consistent with the thermodynamic estimate of around two Earth masses of [[water vapor]] within 3AU of the solar accretionary disk, which would exceed by a factor of 40 the mass of water needed to accrete the equivalent of 50 Earth hydrospheres (the most extreme estimate of Earth's bulk H<sub>2</sub>O content) per terrestrial planet.<ref name = Drake2005/> Even though much of the nebular H<sub>2</sub>O(g) may be lost due to the high temperature environment of the accretionary disk, it is possible for physisorption of H<sub>2</sub>O on accreting grains to retain nearly three Earth hydrospheres of H<sub>2</sub>O at {{convert|500|K|C F}} temperatures.<ref name = Drake2005/> This adsorption model would effectively avoid the <sup>187</sup>Os/<sup>188</sup>Os isotopic ratio disparity issue of distally-sourced H<sub>2</sub>O. However, the current best estimate of the nebular D/H ratio spectroscopically estimated with Jovian and Saturnian atmospheric CH<sub>4</sub> is only 2.1×10<sup>−5</sup>, a factor of 8 lower than Earth's VSMOW ratio.<ref name = Drake2005/> It is unclear how such a difference could exist, if physisorption were indeed the dominant form of H<sub>2</sub>O accretion for Earth in particular and the terrestrial planets in general.
